@node INTRO "INTRODUCTION"

                              @{u}iNTRODUCTION@{uu}

Aehm...in the last public Version (V1.16) I had said that *NO* update of 
this clock will be ever released in the Future...but then 2fAST from 
aRTcORE! had painted a nice charset, so I decided to write another update..:)

During the update, I made again some changings in the code, now it's possible
to define the Date & Location Line for yourself. Detailed Informations for
this could be found in the @{"ToolTypes" LINK TOOLTYPES} - Chapter.

To get a complete overview what changed take a look to the @{b}History-File@{ub} 
included in this archive...let's go on with @{"Installation" LINK INSTALLATION}...
@endnode

@node INSTALLATION "INSTALLATION OF WORLD-CLOCK V1.18"

                       @{u}rEQUIREMENTS & iNSTALLATION@{uu}

Of course you need any Amigamodel (500-4000T) with Kickstart V37++ and a full
installed and working Amiex (Should work under /X V2.xx, too).

Put wORLD-cLOCK V1.18 and the icon wherever you want, but I recommend to 
create an Directory for wORLD-cLOCK, coz wORLD-cLOCK is now able to save the
user-preferences, and they will be saved in the dir wORLD-cLOCK is started
from.

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} In difference to previous versions, wORLD-cLOCK needs @{b}*NO*@{ub} icon anymore
      to run correctly. So if you don't copy the icon to the same drawer the 
      clock is stored, wORLD-cLOCK only shows the local time. The times of 
      the other cities couldn't be displayed, coz you have to define the GMT-
      Time-Offset in the Icon to let wORLD-cLOCK calculates the other times !

Copy the icon `T.info' to your BBSCMD/ drawer and change the Location to the
path where wORLD-cLOCK V1.18 could be found. That's all. To configure the 
Clock to your needs take a look to the @{"Tooltypes" link TOOLTYPES}.

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} Starting from V1.16, every user is able to configure the clock to his 
      own needs, and therefore it's not neccessary that you configure the
      clock in the icon. If you configure it in the Tooltypes, this
      configuration is only the default one which will be overwritten by the
      user's config.
@endnode

@node TOOLTYPES "ALL TOOLTYPES USED BY WORLD-CLOCK V1.18"

                              @{u}tOOLTYPES@{uu}

 LOCATION=<string>       = Here you could enter the Location of your city,
                           i.e. Berlin-Germany. If you don't want to enter
                           a Location, put this Tooltype in Branches. The
                           Clock uses then as location the name of your bbs.

 LOCATION_LINE=<string>  = Here you could define your own default-line for
                           the location from where the time is shown. 
                           Default is :
                           "tIME sHOWING fROM %L" <-- The %L will be replaced
                                                      by your Location !!!

                           This will be used if you don't define this Tool-
                           type.If you want to specify your own, make sure
                           that you don't write too much chars, coz the %L
                           will always replaced by your Location ! Of course
                           you don't have to use the %L command, in this case
                           only the string you have defined will be printed.

DATE_LINE=<STRING>       = This command allows you to define your own Date-
                           line...for this option currently exists two 
                           commands:

                           %T  --> Day (i.e. Wednesday)
                           %D  --> The actual date (i.e. 09-FEB-95)

                           The Defaultsetting for this option is :

                           "actual systemdate is %D (%T)"

                           @{u}NOTE FOR WB 2.1++ USERS:@{uu}
                           Both commands will be translated to the Language,
                           you have defined in your SYS:Prefs/Locale Program.
                           So if you have German as default language, both
                           commands will be translated in :
                          
                           %T = Mittwoch and %D = 09.02.95 
                           
 GMT=<GMT-Time>          = Here you must define your GMT-Time (GMT=Greenwich-
                           MeanTime). For Germany, it's +1. If U don't define
                           this Tooltype, the WoRLD-CLoCK wouldn't be shown,
                           you only see the time from your board.

 LINE_ART=<char>         = If you want to seperate the Clock from the cities,
                           you could enter here *one* char (i.e. -, +, =) and
                           this char will be used to create two lines between
                           the clock and the cities. If you don't want to 
                           seperate it, put this Tooltype in branches or don't 
                           define a char for it.

 CHARSET=<number>        = I've included five different styles for the clock.
                           Here you could choose which one will be used to
                           show the time. Only 0,1,2,3 and 4 are allowed as 
                           valid numbers. The numbers are defined as follow:

                           0 = dIGITS fROM Amblin (Default!) 
                           1 = dIGITS fROM Axe
                           2 = dIGITS fROM Count Zero
                           3 = dIGITS fROM -redSkin
                           4 = dIGITS fROM 2fAST/aRTcORE!
                     
                           To check out the digits, take a look to @{"DIGITS" Link Digits}.

All following ToolTypes are the defines for the colors. Valid colornumbers are
30-37, which represents the ANSI-Colors in /X. I recommend not to use 30, as 
this color is black and you won't see very much if you enter it...:)

 MAIN_COLOR=<color>      = The color for the Title and the Lines between the
                           clock and the cities. Default is 33 (yellow).

 CITY_COLOR=<color>      = The color for "TIME SHOWING FROM.." and the cities.
                           Default is 36 (light blue).

 DIGITS_COLOR=<color>    = The color for the digits and the citytimes. Default
                           is 35 (lila).

 DATELINE_COLOR=<color>  = The Color for the Dateline ( MM-DD-YY (DAY) ).
                           Default is 34 (dark blue).
@endnode

@node ARGS "KNOWN ARGUMENTS GIVEN AT AMIEX-PROMPT"

                             @{u}aRGUMENTS@{uu}
                             
You could start the clock in three different ways...

@{u}1) Normal Start:@{uu} @{b}T@{ub}
This is the easiest way to start the clock...the actual time(s) will be shown
and the clock quits.

@{u}2) Configuration:@{uu} @{b}T E@{ub}
If you start the clock in this mode, you get an optionsscreen which allows 
all users to configure their 'own' clock-style. In Configuration-Mode the 
following options are accessable:

@{b}1@{ub},@{b}2@{ub},@{b}3@{ub},@{b}4@{ub} - Changes the Colors of the clock

   @{b}5@{ub}    - Allows you to change the seperator char

   @{b}6@{ub}    - Select the Digitstyle, available are five different ones. Take a
          look to @{"DIGITS" Link DIGITS} for some examples.

   @{b}7@{ub}    - Select one of five different Date-Formats.

   @{b}S@{ub}    - Save current settings as default ones and display the clock in the
          current settings.

   @{b}P@{ub}    - 'Preview' of current settings..use this if you don't know how the
          current settings looks like...:)

   @{b}A@{ub}    - Use current Settings and start wORLD-cLOCK in Animation-Mode.

   @{b}Q@{ub}    - No saving and reset Settings to default.


@{u}3) Animation:@{uu} @{b}T A@{ub}
In this mode wORLD-cLOCK starts with displaying the time(s), but in 
difference to the normal mode the Local-System-Time will be updated every
second and the World-Times will be updated every minute. To stop the anim
simply press @{b}CTRL-C@{ub} to return to mainprompt.
@endnode

